The Australian Antarctic Division (AAD) is part of the Commonwealth Department of Agriculture, Water and the Environment. As primary agency for Australia's Antarctic Program (AAP), the AAD is responsible for achieving the Australian Government's Antarctic goals. These goals are to:


The AAD also has responsibility for administering the Australian Antarctic Territory and the Territory of Heard and McDonald Islands.

The AAD Science Branch leads, conducts and supports a world class program of scientific research and environmental management, consistent with national priorities through the Australian Antarctic Science Strategic Plan. The branch provides research and advice to support Australia’s Antarctic policy objectives, including participation in the Antarctic Treaty system and other international committees, commissions and intergovernmental panels. It manages and administers the Australian Antarctic Science Program (including project requests, assessment, and reporting) and provides scientific and research advice to support regulatory and management decisions. The branch provides scientific advice for Antarctic capability projects, conducts impact assessments and develops strategies to address environmental legacies and undertakes targeted outreach promoting the value of Australian Antarctic science.

The Antarctic Climate Program investigates a range of Antarctic and Southern Ocean components of the climate system. Its team studies Antarctic atmosphere, sea ice, ice sheets and past climate using ice cores. The Antarctic Climate Program is well integrated within the Australian Antarctic Program Partnership at the University of Tasmania and holds links into the Australian Centre for Excellence in Antarctic Science, an Australian Research Council funded program.

Job Title: Data Scientist, Data Engineer and Data Analyst - Multiple Roles
Job Description:
Job Details

JOB TITLE - Data Scientist, Data Engineer and Data Analyst - Multiple Roles

EMPLOYMENT TYPE - Ongoing Full time

LOCATION - ACT; NSW; QLD; VIC

AFP BAND & SALARY - Band 07, 105,974.00 - 113,500.00

JOB REFERENCE NUMBER - 7596

CONTACT OFFICER - Matthew Curtis, Phone: 0251264681, Email: matt.curtis@afp.gov.au

APPLICATIONS CLOSE - 11:59pm (AEST) 27/10/2021

This advertisement is to fill current vacancies and create a merit pool for future vacancies arising over the next 12 months.

Australian Federal Police

Policing for a safer Australia - the world is changing, crime is changing, we are changing to meet new challenges.

The mission of the AFP is to provide dynamic and effective law enforcement to the people of Australia. It provides policing throughout Australia in relation to the prevention and detection of crimes against the Commonwealth, its laws and integrity, and community police services to the Community of the ACT.

Applications are invited from suitably qualified people who are interested in an appointment to the AFP. Applicants should demonstrate a commitment to the core values of the AFP, and their application must address selection criteria and the relevant work level standards.

The AFP offers a generous remuneration and conditions package, full details can be found here.

As an inclusive organisation, the AFP provides opportunity for all Australians to fairly gain employment in the AFP. We appreciate that everyone is unique and acknowledge that diversity in thought leads to greater transparency and improved consideration in our decision making. To support our employees we also provide flexible work arrangements.

Role Summary

The Australian Federal Police (AFP) is a key player in the Australian security landscape that rises to complex challenges and respond swiftly to protect Australians as new threats emerge. The AFP’s responsibility is to investigate, prevent and disrupt transnational, complex and organised crime; including terrorism, cybercrime, extremism, drug smuggling and human trafficking. The AFP is also responsible for policing in the ACT and other Australian dependent territories, providing protective security for politicians, embassy staff and dignitaries, United Nations peacekeeping and acting as Australia’s international law enforcement representative.

The AFP has embarked on a initiative to use information and data to proactively identify and disrupt criminal activity, and is seeking multiple high quality data analysts, data engineers and data scientists to join the AFP’s Chief Data Officer branch and assist in developing this vision. These roles will directly contribute to the development of AFP’s disruptive capabilities, and to assist the AFP in dynamically combating crime in the digital age. This recruitment activity is aiming to fulfil multiple positions requiring differing skillsets, if you feel like you have something to offer, we encourage you to apply.

The successful candidate(s) will provide expert consultancy within their area of specialism and develop and promote technical analytical solutions which support the business requirements of the AFP.

As a Team Member in the AFP you will be required to contribute to the achievement of outcomes in accordance with the regulatory framework, the AFP Code of Conduct and the AFP Governance Instruments. It is expected that the successful applicant will deliver on the core responsibilities and meet any requirements of the position as outlined below.

If you are passionate in your role as a senior data specialist, and want to make a real difference to Australia’s security and policing future, we want to hear from you!

Role Description & Responsibilities

We are looking for individuals with experience in one or more of the following specialities: data science, data engineering and/or data analysis. The roles are jointly responsible for developing new capabilities, responding to complex data challenges and performing complex data analyses using advanced analytics technologies.

The roles are part of a small section supporting a highly tactical and operational organisation. We run self-sufficient teams where we have all the skills to develop and operate our data capabilities in the team and use scrum to help structure and manage our workload. This gives our team members great opportunity to both broaden and deepen their skills in today's data challenges across many domains and technologies. While roles recruited through this process will be primarily responsible for one of three specialities: data science, data engineering, or data analysis; we also expect our members to jump in and help the broader team when operational demands hit. We recognise that no candidate is going have experience with all the technologies we use, so instead we’re looking for people with a demonstrated ability to learn and adapt quickly to business demands and technological changes. As such, we’re looking for anyone who sees themselves in any of those roles, or a combination of them.


exhibit strong leadership skills,
take the initiative to solve complex problems under minimal supervision,
work collaboratively and communicate well within a self-sufficient scrum team;
develop and support their own and other team members' technical capabilities,
manage day to day activities, and
prioritise completing business requirements.
Essential Requirements


Bachelor’s degree (or higher/equivalent) in mathematics, statistics, computer science, software engineering, information technology or similar.
A Negative Vetting 1 (Secret) security clearance or the ability to obtain one.
Demonstrated experience in modern data analytics, data science and/or data engineering tools
Demonstrated ability to analyse information through the use of modern data analysis tools and analysis languages to solve business problems. This includes an expectation that members can code in at least one data focused language, i.e. Python, SQL, Cypher, R, SAS or similar.
Demonstrated ability and eagerness to take the initiative to learn new technologies quickly
Desirable Requirements


developing with and using modern Natural Language Processing (NLP) technologies
experience in managing the modern machine learning lifecycle, including ability to deploy and support data science models into a production environment
experience in developing with Python, SpaCy, TensorFlow, Keras or similar.
strong analytical skills related to working with structured and unstructured datasets
understanding of modern artificial intelligence and machine learning technologies and techniques
a demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


experience with modern DevSecOps tools and methodologies.
experience in developing with and deploying either batch or streaming data pipelines with any of the following technologies:
Python
Neo4j
Kafka
NiFi
SAS
Impala
Elasticsearch
PostgreSQL
Java
Experience in designing relational and NoSQL data models (especially graph databases).
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


Demonstrated ability to approach and solve complex business problems in innovative ways
Experience in programming and scripting analytical solutions utilising tools such as Python, R or SAS.
Demonstrated ability to communicate solutions to complex problems to key stakeholders
Experience with modern data visualisation tools and business intelligence tools
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains
Selection Criteria

Achieve results
Communicates with influence
Contributes to strategic thinking
Cultivates productive working relationships
Shows personal drive and integrity
Applying technical knowledge, expertise and skills

As part of your application you will be required to submit the following documents:

Applicant response (pitch – maximum two pages)

Advice for Applicants

Application
All mandatory fields must be completed by the applicant. Applicants must provide all requested documents as outlined above in 'Required Application Documents'.

All requested documents must be uploaded to the online application form and submitted before the closing date and time. Any documents not supplied may result in your application being withdrawn from the recruitment process.

The applicant response (pitch) should address the selection criteria and work level standards relevant to the role and provide evidence as to why you are the best fit for the position. The work level standards are specific to the band level of the role you are applying for and can assist in guiding you to address the selection criteria to the level required of the role.

Employment Suitability Requirements
Applicants, who are not current AFP employees, that progress to the next stage of an AFP recruitment process will be required to provide the following documents:

Completed Employment Suitability Questionnaire (ESQ);
Traffic history for the last 10 years; and
Proof of Australian citizenship.

Applicants will be advised by AFP Recruitment if they are required to provide this information. We encourage all applicants to review the AFP’s minimum employment requirements and employment suitability standards to ensure that you meet the set requirements before you submit your application. Applicants whom do not meet these requirements, or fail to provide the required documents, will be removed from the recruitment process.

The Plant Import Operations Branch contributes towards the maintenance of the favourable health status of Australia as well as the maintenance of market access by: coordinating the implementation of national technical operational plant quarantine policy which is consistent with international and national obligations; monitoring of pathways, the technical assessment of import permit applications and issuing import permits for imported plant and plant material; developing and verifying compliance with operational policy, procedures and standards; providing consistent and science based technical advice to staff, clients and stakeholders; and the facilitation of safe importation of plants and plant material. The branch is committed to monitoring, review and improvement and adopting best practice, including using risk-return principles, innovation and project management principles.

The Biosecurity Assurance Program (BAP) identifies, develops and implements business assurance processes for the Branch to ensure import conditions are fit for purpose, biosecurity risks are managed, and business outcomes are achieved. The program is responsible for managing, reviewing and developing training and instructional material for plant import activities, identifying opportunities for risk-return on plant import pathways, through the Compliance-based Intervention Scheme (CBIS), analysing and interpreting import data to inform non-compliance action and business decision making, reviewing intelligence sources to inform changes in risk, policy and processes, managing legislation updates, performing pathway verification activities and supporting a number of other business improvement processes.

The question of ‘Value’ consistently underpins the decision-making process of Boards, management, investors and other stakeholders. Our specialist Valuations team provides value related advice, assisting clients in managing value throughout the business cycle in circumstances relating to M&A transactions, financial reporting, tax, litigation and management decision -making.

Examples of our Work

We supported one of our global industrial products clients in undertaking a valuation of their fixed assets to meet their statutory requirements for Tax and accounting in Australia. Our work involved the valuation of assets across all States & Territories and involved asset inspections and secondary market research.

We assisted one Asia-Pacific’s largest logistics business with a valuation of their assets across the entire APAC region. Tangible asset types included infrastructure and a diverse mobile fleet consisting of light & heavy vehicles, rail rolling stock and aircraft.

We supported a private equity firm understand the tax consequences of the investment strategy they were proposing to execute in respect of a $1b+ acquisition they had undertaken in the business services sector. Our analysis involved understanding the various constituent (tangible and intangible) assets and operations of the multi-national group

What will your typical day look like?

The role involves a mixture of site inspections and on desk valuation modelling, market analysis, research and reporting. A typical engagement will require elements such as asset inspections, data analysis, interactions with operations, engineering, and finance teams, development of replacement costs, useful life analysis, secondary market research and report writing.


Quantifying and articulating value for taxation, transaction, mergers and acquisitions, financing, litigation, financial reporting impairment testing and insurance valuations

Providing independent valuation advice to clients on valuation issues

Developing valuation models for fixed assets based on applying valuation methodologies (market, cost and income approaches)

Calculating values by considering secondary market demand, asset condition, future trends and other factors

Inspecting assets, selecting methods of valuation, and submitting written assessments

Getting exposure to a large cross section of industries and developing appropriate valuation drivers to value the underlying assets

Your ability to manage and analyse multiple valuation projects

Providing fixed asset register analysis, asset register reconciliations and asset register rebuilds

Assisting in the preparation of valuation reports and proposals

Enough about us, let's talk about you

Our preferred candidate is a natural collaborator who is able to think unconventionally, apply commercial thinking and challenge the status quo in designing solutions to real and technical problems. The ideal candidate will be able to demonstrate:

1-2 years (for Analyst role) or 3-4 years (for Senior Analyst role) of experience in a financial, engineering or advisory environment - this is provided as a guide only; please don’t let it limit you if you think you’ve got something to add to our team

Previous fixed asset valuation experience preferred

Ideally Bachelor or Master’s degree in property, engineering, finance, economics, mathematics or data science, with an interest in undertaking a relevant post-graduate qualification (e.g. CA, CFA, MBA or master’s in finance)

Strong MS Office skills (including Excel, PowerPoint and Word) with a particular focus on Excel and data visualisation

Competency in, and a keen interest in further developing, complex valuations/modelling or data analysis

Strong verbal/written communication and interpersonal skills.

Collaborative attitude and ability to develop enthusiasm and commitment from team members and share knowledge

Bioinformatics Analyst
GenieUs Genomics is a young biotechnology company specializing in the development of new biomarkers and treatments for amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), a rapidly progressing neurodegenerative disease with few effective clinical care options. We perform deep, multi-omic analyses of patient cohorts as well as individual patients in order to make discoveries that will fuel rapid advancements in care down to a personalized level. Our research is strongly translational in nature, but we do perform basic research projects as well so as to leave no stone unturned.
We are seeking a Bioinformatics analyst to help us build a bioinformatics platform that can identify the elements of a multi-omic molecular profile that are most likely to drive disease. We are also attempting to use this platform to describe disease subtypes that have so far defied description in around 90% of the ALS population.

Our Agency
The Australian Signals Directorate (ASD) is an Australian Government intelligence and security agency.

The ASD motto, Reveal their secrets - Protect our own, summarises our roles: we collect foreign intelligence; we provide advice and assistance on information and cyber security; and we conduct offensive cyber operations.

To achieve its mission, ASD requires people with strong integrity and a mix of specialist skills, adaptability, imagination, resilience and creativity.

These abilities are needed to out-think and out-imagine some of the most testing adversaries and problems imaginable. ASD operates in the slim area between the difficult and the impossible. If you want to work with other smart, skilled people, ASD has an opportunity for you.

What can ASD offer you? Challenging, interesting and unique work that directly supports the Australian Defence Force and Australian Government decision-making; ongoing commitment to staff training including technical, business and interpersonal skills; close-knit and supportive work teams; and the possibility of national and international travel opportunities.

ASD value their employees and provide them flexible working arrangements, diverse career paths, a supportive work environment, study assistance opportunities, social and networking opportunities, support of casual dress, pay increases linked to regular performance reviews and relocation assistance for successful applicants.

About the Roles

Analysts at ASD use their technical capabilities, in multi-disciplinary teams to solve problems that others cannot solve. They receive training in using our specialised systems, which are used to undertake sophisticated intelligence or technical analysis, producing vital intelligence and security information for the Australian Government.

Analysts may have opportunities to travel domestically and internationally, and are encouraged to develop and redevelop their skills to keep pace with evolving priorities.



If you have skills in languages other than English (LOTE) you may be interested in a career as a foreign language analyst. For more information or to apply for a foreign language analyst role please refer to the Rolling Recruitment - Language Careers vacancies.

ASD continues to grow and is continually looking for talented people to join our mission.
This will be a rolling-recruitment process, which means it will be conducted regularly. If you are successful in the application and assessment process you will be placed in a merit pool and may be contacted for further testing as positions become available. These may be ongoing or non-ongoing opportunities.

Throughout the year, ASD may contact you to reconfirm your interest in roles and update you with any relevant information. We request that you also let us know if your circumstances change and you no longer wish to remain in the merit pool.

Role Summary

We are looking for experienced data analysts who are able to turn data into information, information into insight and insight into business decisions.

The successful applicant will be able to interpret data and provide easy to understand reports for AFP executive and internal and external stakeholders. To perform this role at the required level you will need an eye for detail, ability to manage master data sets, develop reports, troubleshoot data issues and have a strong understanding of data analysis tools and data bases.

This role is located in Professional Standards.

As a Team Member in the AFP you will be required to contribute to the achievement of outcomes in accordance with the regulatory framework, the AFP Code of Conduct and the AFP Governance Instruments. It is expected that the successful applicant will deliver on the core responsibilities and meet any requirements of the position as outlined below.

Role Description & Responsibilities

A successful applicant for this role will be required to contribute to the achievement of outcomes in relation to the analysis of data and information and the production of regular and ad hoc reports, predominately for internal stakeholders. This work may include:

Using AFP tools and systems, such as SAS Visual Analytics, to access, search, map and analyse various forms of data to inform analysis and reporting.
Communicating information and analytical data verbally, visually (including the creation of dashboards) and in written material to stakeholders.
Generate easy to interpret reports based on collected data.
Analysing data to identify trends, patterns and specific issues to guide the direction of operational and organisational change.
Interpreting data, analysing results using statistical techniques.
Quality assurance of data to ensure compatibility with requests, and accuracy of data input.
Providing specific recommendations about what data needs tracking and how it can be used to benefit the organisation.
Liaison with internal and external stakeholders to support and guide best practice data collection.
Maintaining currency in data analysis processes and technical knowledge through ongoing development and learning opportunities outside the formal education process.

This role predominantly involves working independently and as part of a team to extract, evaluate and communicate data and analytical information.

Essential Requirements

Must be an Australian Citizen.
Negative Vetting 1 (Secret) security clearance or the ability to obtain one.
Qualifications and/or demonstrated skills and experience in data analysis and corporate reporting.
Desirable Requirements

Demonstrated experience using SAS Visual Analytics or a similar visual analytics tool.

Organising your work, making sound decisions and achieving outcomes

The Role

The Australian Hydrographic Office (AHO) is Australia’s national hydrographic and charting authority and is responsible for producing nautical charts and other products in support of Australia’s maritime interests and Defence operations, ensuring safety and environment protection.

This Office is seeking people who have qualifications or experience in spatial or physical sciences to contribute towards achieving our business outcomes.

As a Geospatial Analyst with the AHO you will work to ingest, manage and validate geospatial data related to the maritime environment or turn this data into navigation products and services. You will work in geographic information systems to specifications and standards to ensure quality and consistency of output.

You will have an opportunity to combine an exceptional and meaningful career with a highly desirable coastal lifestyle where you will have access to excellent workplace conditions and working arrangements.

A merit pool will be formed from this recruitment activity, and candidates may be required to have a security clearance level ranging from Baseline Vetting to Positive Vetting.



Our teams are technically focussed with a range of subject matter experts in marine data complexities. We work together to flow source data, through validation and quality assessment tasks, then on to the production and dissemination processes. Our tasks are guided via work flow and Quality Management Systems and international and national standards and specifications.

We provide an open plan office working environment that offers you a range of work, flexibility to be innovative, talented colleagues, a focus on training and development and the guidance and support to ensure that you always have everything that you need to succeed.

Company description
OzTAM is Australia’s official source of television audience measurement, covering free-to-air and subscription television in the five metropolitan markets (Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Adelaide, and Perth) and subscription television nationally. OzTAM TV ratings are the accepted metric by which Australian television is evaluated. The media industry uses OzTAM data to assist in program development, advertising planning, and to gauge the performance of television programs, networks, and advertising campaigns.
OzTAM’s Video Player Measurement (VPM) provides Australia’s official figures for the audience viewing internet-delivered broadcast TV content (BVOD).
In 2021, OzTAM, Nielsen, and Regional TAM launch the foundation of Australia’s new Total TV currency, Virtual Australia (‘VOZ’), which brings together broadcast viewing on in-home TV sets ( metro and regional linear TV ratings) and connected devices (VPM, measuring broadcast video on demand, or ‘BVOD’) to provide an all-screen, cross-platform planning and reporting standard for Australia’s television industry.

Our Agency
The Australian Signals Directorate (ASD) is an Australian Government intelligence and security agency.

The ASD motto, Reveal their secrets - Protect our own, summarises our roles: we collect foreign intelligence; we provide advice and assistance on information and cyber security; and we conduct offensive cyber operations.

To achieve its mission, ASD requires people with strong integrity and a mix of specialist skills, adaptability, imagination, resilience and creativity.

These abilities are needed to out-think and out-imagine some of the most testing adversaries and problems imaginable. ASD operates in the slim area between the difficult and the impossible. If you want to work with other smart, skilled people, ASD has an opportunity for you.

What can ASD offer you? Challenging, interesting and unique work that directly supports the Australian Defence Force and Australian Government decision-making; ongoing commitment to staff training including technical, business and interpersonal skills; close-knit and supportive work teams; and the possibility of national and international travel opportunities.

ASD value their employees and provide them flexible working arrangements, diverse career paths, a supportive work environment, study assistance opportunities, social and networking opportunities, support of casual dress, pay increases linked to regular performance reviews and relocation assistance for successful applicants.

About the Roles

Analysts at ASD use their technical capabilities, in multi-disciplinary teams to solve problems that others cannot solve. They receive training in using our specialised systems, which are used to undertake sophisticated intelligence or technical analysis, producing vital intelligence and security information for the Australian Government.

Analysts may have opportunities to travel domestically and internationally, and are encouraged to develop and redevelop their skills to keep pace with evolving priorities.



If you have skills in languages other than English (LOTE) you may be interested in a career as a foreign language analyst. For more information or to apply for a foreign language analyst role please refer to the Rolling Recruitment - Language Careers vacancies.

This will be a rolling-recruitment process, which means it will be conducted regularly. These may be ongoing or non-ongoing opportunities.

Job Description:

Australian Federal Police

Policing for a safer Australia - the world is changing, crime is changing, we are changing to meet new challenges.

The mission of the AFP is to provide dynamic and effective law enforcement to the people of Australia. It provides policing throughout Australia in relation to the prevention and detection of crimes against the Commonwealth, its laws and integrity, and community police services to the Community of the ACT.

Applications are invited from suitably qualified people who are interested in an appointment to the AFP. Applicants should demonstrate a commitment to the core values of the AFP, and their application must address selection criteria and the relevant work level standards.

The AFP offers a generous remuneration and conditions package, full details can be found here.

As an inclusive organisation, the AFP provides opportunity for all Australians to fairly gain employment in the AFP. We appreciate that everyone is unique and acknowledge that diversity in thought leads to greater transparency and improved consideration in our decision making. To support our employees we also provide flexible work arrangements.

Role Summary

The Australian Federal Police (AFP) is a key player in the Australian security landscape that rises to complex challenges and respond swiftly to protect Australians as new threats emerge. The AFP’s responsibility is to investigate, prevent and disrupt transnational, complex and organised crime; including terrorism, cybercrime, extremism, drug smuggling and human trafficking. The AFP is also responsible for policing in the ACT and other Australian dependent territories, providing protective security for politicians, embassy staff and dignitaries, United Nations peacekeeping and acting as Australia’s international law enforcement representative.

The AFP has embarked on a initiative to use information and data to proactively identify and disrupt criminal activity, and is seeking multiple high quality data analysts, data engineers and data scientists to join the AFP’s Chief Data Officer branch and assist in developing this vision. These roles will directly contribute to the development of AFP’s disruptive capabilities, and to assist the AFP in dynamically combating crime in the digital age. This recruitment activity is aiming to fulfil multiple positions requiring differing skillsets, if you feel like you have something to offer, we encourage you to apply.

The successful candidate(s) will provide expert consultancy within their area of specialism and develop and promote technical analytical solutions which support the business requirements of the AFP.

As a Team Member in the AFP you will be required to contribute to the achievement of outcomes in accordance with the regulatory framework, the AFP Code of Conduct and the AFP Governance Instruments. It is expected that the successful applicant will deliver on the core responsibilities and meet any requirements of the position as outlined below.

If you are passionate in your role as a senior data specialist, and want to make a real difference to Australia’s security and policing future, we want to hear from you!

Role Description & Responsibilities

We are looking for individuals with experience in one or more of the following specialities: data science, data engineering and/or data analysis. The roles are jointly responsible for developing new capabilities, responding to complex data challenges and performing complex data analyses using advanced analytics technologies.

The roles are part of a small section supporting a highly tactical and operational organisation. We run self-sufficient teams where we have all the skills to develop and operate our data capabilities in the team and use scrum to help structure and manage our workload. This gives our team members great opportunity to both broaden and deepen their skills in today's data challenges across many domains and technologies. While roles recruited through this process will be primarily responsible for one of three specialities: data science, data engineering, or data analysis; we also expect our members to jump in and help the broader team when operational demands hit. We recognise that no candidate is going have experience with all the technologies we use, so instead we’re looking for people with a demonstrated ability to learn and adapt quickly to business demands and technological changes. As such, we’re looking for anyone who sees themselves in any of those roles, or a combination of them.


exhibit strong leadership skills,
take the initiative to solve complex problems under minimal supervision,
work collaboratively and communicate well within a self-sufficient scrum team;
develop and support their own and other team members' technical capabilities,
manage day to day activities, and
prioritise completing business requirements.
Essential Requirements


Bachelor’s degree (or higher/equivalent) in mathematics, statistics, computer science, software engineering, information technology or similar.
A Negative Vetting 1 (Secret) security clearance or the ability to obtain one.
Demonstrated experience in modern data analytics, data science and/or data engineering tools
Demonstrated ability to analyse information through the use of modern data analysis tools and analysis languages to solve business problems. This includes an expectation that members can code in at least one data focused language, i.e. Python, SQL, Cypher, R, SAS or similar.
Demonstrated ability and eagerness to take the initiative to learn new technologies quickly
Desirable Requirements


developing with and using modern Natural Language Processing (NLP) technologies
experience in managing the modern machine learning lifecycle, including ability to deploy and support data science models into a production environment
experience in developing with Python, SpaCy, TensorFlow, Keras or similar.
strong analytical skills related to working with structured and unstructured datasets
understanding of modern artificial intelligence and machine learning technologies and techniques
a demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


experience with modern DevSecOps tools and methodologies.
experience in developing with and deploying either batch or streaming data pipelines with any of the following technologies:
Python
Neo4j
Kafka
NiFi
SAS
Impala
Elasticsearch
PostgreSQL
Java
Experience in designing relational and NoSQL data models (especially graph databases).
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


Demonstrated ability to approach and solve complex business problems in innovative ways
Experience in programming and scripting analytical solutions utilising tools such as Python, R or SAS.
Demonstrated ability to communicate solutions to complex problems to key stakeholders
Experience with modern data visualisation tools and business intelligence tools
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains
Selection Criteria

Achieve results
Communicates with influence
Contributes to strategic thinking
Cultivates productive working relationships
Shows personal drive and integrity
Applying technical knowledge, expertise and skills

Applicant response (pitch – maximum two pages)
Resume/CV
Tertiary education certificate/s

Application
All mandatory fields must be completed by the applicant. Applicants must provide all requested documents as outlined above in 'Required Application Documents'.

All requested documents must be uploaded to the online application form and submitted before the closing date and time. Any documents not supplied may result in your application being withdrawn from the recruitment process.

The applicant response (pitch) should address the selection criteria and work level standards relevant to the role and provide evidence as to why you are the best fit for the position. The work level standards are specific to the band level of the role you are applying for and can assist in guiding you to address the selection criteria to the level required of the role.

Employment Suitability Requirements
Applicants, who are not current AFP employees, that progress to the next stage of an AFP recruitment process will be required to provide the following documents:

Completed Employment Suitability Questionnaire (ESQ);
Traffic history for the last 10 years; and
Proof of Australian citizenship.

Applicants will be advised by AFP Recruitment if they are required to provide this information. Applicants whom do not meet these requirements, or fail to provide the required documents, will be removed from the recruitment process.

The Plant Import Operations Branch contributes towards the maintenance of the favourable health status of Australia as well as the maintenance of market access by: coordinating the implementation of national technical operational plant quarantine policy which is consistent with international and national obligations; monitoring of pathways, the technical assessment of import permit applications and issuing import permits for imported plant and plant material; developing and verifying compliance with operational policy, procedures and standards; providing consistent and science based technical advice to staff, clients and stakeholders; and the facilitation of safe importation of plants and plant material. The branch is committed to monitoring, review and improvement and adopting best practice, including using risk-return principles, innovation and project management principles.

The Biosecurity Assurance Program (BAP) identifies, develops and implements business assurance processes for the Branch to ensure import conditions are fit for purpose, biosecurity risks are managed, and business outcomes are achieved. The program is responsible for managing, reviewing and developing training and instructional material for plant import activities, identifying opportunities for risk-return on plant import pathways, through the Compliance-based Intervention Scheme (CBIS), analysing and interpreting import data to inform non-compliance action and business decision making, reviewing intelligence sources to inform changes in risk, policy and processes, managing legislation updates, performing pathway verification activities and supporting a number of other business improvement processes.

Job Title: Data Scientist, Data Engineer and Data Analyst - Multiple Roles
Job Description:
Job Details

EMPLOYMENT TYPE - Ongoing Full time

AFP BAND & SALARY - Band 07, 105,974.00 - 113,500.00

This advertisement is to fill current vacancies and create a merit pool for future vacancies arising over the next 12 months.

Australian Federal Police

Policing for a safer Australia - the world is changing, crime is changing, we are changing to meet new challenges.

The mission of the AFP is to provide dynamic and effective law enforcement to the people of Australia. It provides policing throughout Australia in relation to the prevention and detection of crimes against the Commonwealth, its laws and integrity, and community police services to the Community of the ACT.

Applications are invited from suitably qualified people who are interested in an appointment to the AFP. Applicants should demonstrate a commitment to the core values of the AFP, and their application must address selection criteria and the relevant work level standards.

The AFP offers a generous remuneration and conditions package, full details can be found here.

As an inclusive organisation, the AFP provides opportunity for all Australians to fairly gain employment in the AFP. We appreciate that everyone is unique and acknowledge that diversity in thought leads to greater transparency and improved consideration in our decision making. To support our employees we also provide flexible work arrangements.

Role Summary

The Australian Federal Police (AFP) is a key player in the Australian security landscape that rises to complex challenges and respond swiftly to protect Australians as new threats emerge. The AFP’s responsibility is to investigate, prevent and disrupt transnational, complex and organised crime; including terrorism, cybercrime, extremism, drug smuggling and human trafficking. The AFP is also responsible for policing in the ACT and other Australian dependent territories, providing protective security for politicians, embassy staff and dignitaries, United Nations peacekeeping and acting as Australia’s international law enforcement representative.

The AFP has embarked on a initiative to use information and data to proactively identify and disrupt criminal activity, and is seeking multiple high quality data analysts, data engineers and data scientists to join the AFP’s Chief Data Officer branch and assist in developing this vision. These roles will directly contribute to the development of AFP’s disruptive capabilities, and to assist the AFP in dynamically combating crime in the digital age. This recruitment activity is aiming to fulfil multiple positions requiring differing skillsets, if you feel like you have something to offer, we encourage you to apply.

The successful candidate(s) will provide expert consultancy within their area of specialism and develop and promote technical analytical solutions which support the business requirements of the AFP.

As a Team Member in the AFP you will be required to contribute to the achievement of outcomes in accordance with the regulatory framework, the AFP Code of Conduct and the AFP Governance Instruments. It is expected that the successful applicant will deliver on the core responsibilities and meet any requirements of the position as outlined below.

If you are passionate in your role as a senior data specialist, and want to make a real difference to Australia’s security and policing future, we want to hear from you!

Role Description & Responsibilities

We are looking for individuals with experience in one or more of the following specialities: data science, data engineering and/or data analysis. The roles are jointly responsible for developing new capabilities, responding to complex data challenges and performing complex data analyses using advanced analytics technologies.

The roles are part of a small section supporting a highly tactical and operational organisation. We run self-sufficient teams where we have all the skills to develop and operate our data capabilities in the team and use scrum to help structure and manage our workload. This gives our team members great opportunity to both broaden and deepen their skills in today's data challenges across many domains and technologies. While roles recruited through this process will be primarily responsible for one of three specialities: data science, data engineering, or data analysis; we also expect our members to jump in and help the broader team when operational demands hit. We recognise that no candidate is going have experience with all the technologies we use, so instead we’re looking for people with a demonstrated ability to learn and adapt quickly to business demands and technological changes. As such, we’re looking for anyone who sees themselves in any of those roles, or a combination of them.


exhibit strong leadership skills,
take the initiative to solve complex problems under minimal supervision,
work collaboratively and communicate well within a self-sufficient scrum team;
develop and support their own and other team members' technical capabilities,
manage day to day activities, and
prioritise completing business requirements.
Essential Requirements


Bachelor’s degree (or higher/equivalent) in mathematics, statistics, computer science, software engineering, information technology or similar.
A Negative Vetting 1 (Secret) security clearance or the ability to obtain one.
Demonstrated experience in modern data analytics, data science and/or data engineering tools
Demonstrated ability to analyse information through the use of modern data analysis tools and analysis languages to solve business problems. This includes an expectation that members can code in at least one data focused language, i.e. Python, SQL, Cypher, R, SAS or similar.
Demonstrated ability and eagerness to take the initiative to learn new technologies quickly
Desirable Requirements


developing with and using modern Natural Language Processing (NLP) technologies
experience in managing the modern machine learning lifecycle, including ability to deploy and support data science models into a production environment
experience in developing with Python, SpaCy, TensorFlow, Keras or similar.
strong analytical skills related to working with structured and unstructured datasets
understanding of modern artificial intelligence and machine learning technologies and techniques
a demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


experience with modern DevSecOps tools and methodologies.
experience in developing with and deploying either batch or streaming data pipelines with any of the following technologies:
Python
Neo4j
Kafka
NiFi
SAS
Impala
Elasticsearch
PostgreSQL
Java
Experience in designing relational and NoSQL data models (especially graph databases).
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


Demonstrated ability to approach and solve complex business problems in innovative ways
Experience in programming and scripting analytical solutions utilising tools such as Python, R or SAS.
Demonstrated ability to communicate solutions to complex problems to key stakeholders
Experience with modern data visualisation tools and business intelligence tools
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains
Selection Criteria

Achieve results
Communicates with influence
Contributes to strategic thinking
Cultivates productive working relationships
Shows personal drive and integrity
Applying technical knowledge, expertise and skills
Required Application Documents

As part of your application you will be required to submit the following documents:

Applicant response (pitch – maximum two pages)
Resume/CV
Tertiary education certificate/s
Advice for Applicants

Application
All mandatory fields must be completed by the applicant. Applicants must provide all requested documents as outlined above in 'Required Application Documents'.

All requested documents must be uploaded to the online application form and submitted before the closing date and time. Any documents not supplied may result in your application being withdrawn from the recruitment process.

The applicant response (pitch) should address the selection criteria and work level standards relevant to the role and provide evidence as to why you are the best fit for the position. The work level standards are specific to the band level of the role you are applying for and can assist in guiding you to address the selection criteria to the level required of the role.

Employment Suitability Requirements
Applicants, who are not current AFP employees, that progress to the next stage of an AFP recruitment process will be required to provide the following documents:

Completed Employment Suitability Questionnaire (ESQ);
Traffic history for the last 10 years; and
Proof of Australian citizenship.

Applicants will be advised by AFP Recruitment if they are required to provide this information. We encourage all applicants to review the AFP’s minimum employment requirements and employment suitability standards to ensure that you meet the set requirements before you submit your application. Applicants whom do not meet these requirements, or fail to provide the required documents, will be removed from the recruitment process.

For further information on other employment opportunities in the AFP, please visit our website.

The Plant Import Operations Branch contributes towards the maintenance of the favourable health status of Australia as well as the maintenance of market access by: coordinating the implementation of national technical operational plant quarantine policy which is consistent with international and national obligations; monitoring of pathways, the technical assessment of import permit applications and issuing import permits for imported plant and plant material; developing and verifying compliance with operational policy, procedures and standards; providing consistent and science based technical advice to staff, clients and stakeholders; and the facilitation of safe importation of plants and plant material. The branch is committed to monitoring, review and improvement and adopting best practice, including using risk-return principles, innovation and project management principles.

The Biosecurity Assurance Program (BAP) identifies, develops and implements business assurance processes for the Branch to ensure import conditions are fit for purpose, biosecurity risks are managed, and business outcomes are achieved. The program is responsible for managing, reviewing and developing training and instructional material for plant import activities, identifying opportunities for risk-return on plant import pathways, through the Compliance-based Intervention Scheme (CBIS), analysing and interpreting import data to inform non-compliance action and business decision making, reviewing intelligence sources to inform changes in risk, policy and processes, managing legislation updates, performing pathway verification activities and supporting a number of other business improvement processes.

Job Description:
Job Details

JOB TITLE - Data Scientist, Data Engineer and Data Analyst - Multiple Roles

EMPLOYMENT TYPE - Ongoing Full time

This advertisement is to fill current vacancies and create a merit pool for future vacancies arising over the next 12 months.

Australian Federal Police

Policing for a safer Australia - the world is changing, crime is changing, we are changing to meet new challenges.

The mission of the AFP is to provide dynamic and effective law enforcement to the people of Australia. It provides policing throughout Australia in relation to the prevention and detection of crimes against the Commonwealth, its laws and integrity, and community police services to the Community of the ACT.

Applications are invited from suitably qualified people who are interested in an appointment to the AFP. Applicants should demonstrate a commitment to the core values of the AFP, and their application must address selection criteria and the relevant work level standards.

The AFP offers a generous remuneration and conditions package, full details can be found here.

As an inclusive organisation, the AFP provides opportunity for all Australians to fairly gain employment in the AFP. We appreciate that everyone is unique and acknowledge that diversity in thought leads to greater transparency and improved consideration in our decision making. To support our employees we also provide flexible work arrangements.

Role Summary

The Australian Federal Police (AFP) is a key player in the Australian security landscape that rises to complex challenges and respond swiftly to protect Australians as new threats emerge. The AFP’s responsibility is to investigate, prevent and disrupt transnational, complex and organised crime; including terrorism, cybercrime, extremism, drug smuggling and human trafficking. The AFP is also responsible for policing in the ACT and other Australian dependent territories, providing protective security for politicians, embassy staff and dignitaries, United Nations peacekeeping and acting as Australia’s international law enforcement representative.

The AFP has embarked on a initiative to use information and data to proactively identify and disrupt criminal activity, and is seeking multiple high quality data analysts, data engineers and data scientists to join the AFP’s Chief Data Officer branch and assist in developing this vision. These roles will directly contribute to the development of AFP’s disruptive capabilities, and to assist the AFP in dynamically combating crime in the digital age. This recruitment activity is aiming to fulfil multiple positions requiring differing skillsets, if you feel like you have something to offer, we encourage you to apply.

The successful candidate(s) will provide expert consultancy within their area of specialism and develop and promote technical analytical solutions which support the business requirements of the AFP.

As a Team Member in the AFP you will be required to contribute to the achievement of outcomes in accordance with the regulatory framework, the AFP Code of Conduct and the AFP Governance Instruments. It is expected that the successful applicant will deliver on the core responsibilities and meet any requirements of the position as outlined below.

If you are passionate in your role as a senior data specialist, and want to make a real difference to Australia’s security and policing future, we want to hear from you!

Role Description & Responsibilities

We are looking for individuals with experience in one or more of the following specialities: data science, data engineering and/or data analysis. The roles are jointly responsible for developing new capabilities, responding to complex data challenges and performing complex data analyses using advanced analytics technologies.

The roles are part of a small section supporting a highly tactical and operational organisation. We run self-sufficient teams where we have all the skills to develop and operate our data capabilities in the team and use scrum to help structure and manage our workload. This gives our team members great opportunity to both broaden and deepen their skills in today's data challenges across many domains and technologies. While roles recruited through this process will be primarily responsible for one of three specialities: data science, data engineering, or data analysis; we also expect our members to jump in and help the broader team when operational demands hit. We recognise that no candidate is going have experience with all the technologies we use, so instead we’re looking for people with a demonstrated ability to learn and adapt quickly to business demands and technological changes. As such, we’re looking for anyone who sees themselves in any of those roles, or a combination of them.


exhibit strong leadership skills,
take the initiative to solve complex problems under minimal supervision,
work collaboratively and communicate well within a self-sufficient scrum team;
develop and support their own and other team members' technical capabilities,
manage day to day activities, and
prioritise completing business requirements.
Essential Requirements


Bachelor’s degree (or higher/equivalent) in mathematics, statistics, computer science, software engineering, information technology or similar.
A Negative Vetting 1 (Secret) security clearance or the ability to obtain one.
Demonstrated experience in modern data analytics, data science and/or data engineering tools
Demonstrated ability to analyse information through the use of modern data analysis tools and analysis languages to solve business problems. This includes an expectation that members can code in at least one data focused language, i.e. Python, SQL, Cypher, R, SAS or similar.
Demonstrated ability and eagerness to take the initiative to learn new technologies quickly
Desirable Requirements


developing with and using modern Natural Language Processing (NLP) technologies
experience in managing the modern machine learning lifecycle, including ability to deploy and support data science models into a production environment
experience in developing with Python, SpaCy, TensorFlow, Keras or similar.
strong analytical skills related to working with structured and unstructured datasets
understanding of modern artificial intelligence and machine learning technologies and techniques
a demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


experience with modern DevSecOps tools and methodologies.
experience in developing with and deploying either batch or streaming data pipelines with any of the following technologies:
Python
Neo4j
Kafka
NiFi
SAS
Impala
Elasticsearch
PostgreSQL
Java
Experience in designing relational and NoSQL data models (especially graph databases).
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


Demonstrated ability to approach and solve complex business problems in innovative ways
Experience in programming and scripting analytical solutions utilising tools such as Python, R or SAS.
Demonstrated ability to communicate solutions to complex problems to key stakeholders
Experience with modern data visualisation tools and business intelligence tools
A demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains
Selection Criteria

Achieve results
Communicates with influence
Contributes to strategic thinking
Cultivates productive working relationships
Shows personal drive and integrity
Applying technical knowledge, expertise and skills
Required Application Documents

As part of your application you will be required to submit the following documents:

Applicant response (pitch – maximum two pages)
Resume/CV
Tertiary education certificate/s
Advice for Applicants

Application
All mandatory fields must be completed by the applicant. Applicants must provide all requested documents as outlined above in 'Required Application Documents'.

All requested documents must be uploaded to the online application form and submitted before the closing date and time. Any documents not supplied may result in your application being withdrawn from the recruitment process.

The applicant response (pitch) should address the selection criteria and work level standards relevant to the role and provide evidence as to why you are the best fit for the position. The work level standards are specific to the band level of the role you are applying for and can assist in guiding you to address the selection criteria to the level required of the role.

Employment Suitability Requirements
Applicants, who are not current AFP employees, that progress to the next stage of an AFP recruitment process will be required to provide the following documents:

Completed Employment Suitability Questionnaire (ESQ);
Traffic history for the last 10 years; and
Proof of Australian citizenship.

Applicants will be advised by AFP Recruitment if they are required to provide this information. We encourage all applicants to review the AFP’s minimum employment requirements and employment suitability standards to ensure that you meet the set requirements before you submit your application. Applicants whom do not meet these requirements, or fail to provide the required documents, will be removed from the recruitment process.

For further information on other employment opportunities in the AFP, please visit our website.

The Plant Import Operations Branch contributes towards the maintenance of the favourable health status of Australia as well as the maintenance of market access by: coordinating the implementation of national technical operational plant quarantine policy which is consistent with international and national obligations; monitoring of pathways, the technical assessment of import permit applications and issuing import permits for imported plant and plant material; developing and verifying compliance with operational policy, procedures and standards; providing consistent and science based technical advice to staff, clients and stakeholders; and the facilitation of safe importation of plants and plant material. The branch is committed to monitoring, review and improvement and adopting best practice, including using risk-return principles, innovation and project management principles.

The Biosecurity Assurance Program (BAP) identifies, develops and implements business assurance processes for the Branch to ensure import conditions are fit for purpose, biosecurity risks are managed, and business outcomes are achieved. The program is responsible for managing, reviewing and developing training and instructional material for plant import activities, identifying opportunities for risk-return on plant import pathways, through the Compliance-based Intervention Scheme (CBIS), analysing and interpreting import data to inform non-compliance action and business decision making, reviewing intelligence sources to inform changes in risk, policy and processes, managing legislation updates, performing pathway verification activities and supporting a number of other business improvement processes.

The Australian Antarctic Division (AAD) is part of the Commonwealth Department of Agriculture, Water and the Environment. As primary agency for Australia's Antarctic Program (AAP), the AAD is responsible for achieving the Australian Government's Antarctic goals. These goals are to:


The AAD also has responsibility for administering the Australian Antarctic Territory and the Territory of Heard and McDonald Islands.

The AAD Science Branch leads, conducts and supports a world class program of scientific research and environmental management, consistent with national priorities through the Australian Antarctic Science Strategic Plan. The branch provides research and advice to support Australia’s Antarctic policy objectives, including participation in the Antarctic Treaty system and other international committees, commissions and intergovernmental panels. It manages and administers the Australian Antarctic Science Program (including project requests, assessment, and reporting) and provides scientific and research advice to support regulatory and management decisions. The branch provides scientific advice for Antarctic capability projects, conducts impact assessments and develops strategies to address environmental legacies and undertakes targeted outreach promoting the value of Australian Antarctic science.

The Antarctic Climate Program investigates a range of Antarctic and Southern Ocean components of the climate system. Its team studies Antarctic atmosphere, sea ice, ice sheets and past climate using ice cores. The Antarctic Climate Program is well integrated within the Australian Antarctic Program Partnership at the University of Tasmania and holds links into the Australian Centre for Excellence in Antarctic Science, an Australian Research Council funded program.

Australian Federal Police

Policing for a safer Australia - the world is changing, crime is changing, we are changing to meet new challenges.

The mission of the AFP is to provide dynamic and effective law enforcement to the people of Australia. It provides policing throughout Australia in relation to the prevention and detection of crimes against the Commonwealth, its laws and integrity, and community police services to the Community of the ACT.

Applications are invited from suitably qualified people who are interested in an appointment to the AFP. Applicants should demonstrate a commitment to the core values of the AFP, and their application must address selection criteria and the relevant work level standards.

The AFP offers a generous remuneration and conditions package, full details can be found here.

As an inclusive organisation, the AFP provides opportunity for all Australians to fairly gain employment in the AFP. We appreciate that everyone is unique and acknowledge that diversity in thought leads to greater transparency and improved consideration in our decision making. To support our employees we also provide flexible work arrangements.

Role Summary

The Australian Federal Police (AFP) is a key player in the Australian security landscape that rises to complex challenges and respond swiftly to protect Australians as new threats emerge. The AFP’s responsibility is to investigate, prevent and disrupt transnational, complex and organised crime; including terrorism, cybercrime, extremism, drug smuggling and human trafficking. The AFP is also responsible for policing in the ACT and other Australian dependent territories, providing protective security for politicians, embassy staff and dignitaries, United Nations peacekeeping and acting as Australia’s international law enforcement representative.

The AFP has embarked on a initiative to use information and data to proactively identify and disrupt criminal activity, and is seeking multiple high quality data analysts, data engineers and data scientists to join the AFP’s Chief Data Officer branch and assist in developing this vision. These roles will directly contribute to the development of AFP’s disruptive capabilities, and to assist the AFP in dynamically combating crime in the digital age. This recruitment activity is aiming to fulfil multiple positions requiring differing skillsets, if you feel like you have something to offer, we encourage you to apply.

The successful candidate(s) will provide expert consultancy within their area of specialism and develop and promote technical analytical solutions which support the business requirements of the AFP.

As a Team Member in the AFP you will be required to contribute to the achievement of outcomes in accordance with the regulatory framework, the AFP Code of Conduct and the AFP Governance Instruments. It is expected that the successful applicant will deliver on the core responsibilities and meet any requirements of the position as outlined below.

If you are passionate in your role as a senior data specialist, and want to make a real difference to Australia’s security and policing future, we want to hear from you!

Role Description & Responsibilities

We are looking for individuals with experience in one or more of the following specialities: data science, data engineering and/or data analysis. The roles are jointly responsible for developing new capabilities, responding to complex data challenges and performing complex data analyses using advanced analytics technologies.

The roles are part of a small section supporting a highly tactical and operational organisation. We run self-sufficient teams where we have all the skills to develop and operate our data capabilities in the team and use scrum to help structure and manage our workload. This gives our team members great opportunity to both broaden and deepen their skills in today's data challenges across many domains and technologies. While roles recruited through this process will be primarily responsible for one of three specialities: data science, data engineering, or data analysis; we also expect our members to jump in and help the broader team when operational demands hit. We recognise that no candidate is going have experience with all the technologies we use, so instead we’re looking for people with a demonstrated ability to learn and adapt quickly to business demands and technological changes. As such, we’re looking for anyone who sees themselves in any of those roles, or a combination of them.


exhibit strong leadership skills,
take the initiative to solve complex problems under minimal supervision,
work collaboratively and communicate well within a self-sufficient scrum team;
develop and support their own and other team members' technical capabilities,
manage day to day activities, and
prioritise completing business requirements.
Essential Requirements


Bachelor’s degree (or higher/equivalent) in mathematics, statistics, computer science, software engineering, information technology or similar.
A Negative Vetting 1 (Secret) security clearance or the ability to obtain one.
Demonstrated experience in modern data analytics, data science and/or data engineering tools
Demonstrated ability to analyse information through the use of modern data analysis tools and analysis languages to solve business problems. This includes an expectation that members can code in at least one data focused language, i.e. Python, SQL, Cypher, R, SAS or similar.
Demonstrated ability and eagerness to take the initiative to learn new technologies quickly
Desirable Requirements


developing with and using modern Natural Language Processing (NLP) technologies
experience in managing the modern machine learning lifecycle, including ability to deploy and support data science models into a production environment
experience in developing with Python, SpaCy, TensorFlow, Keras or similar.
strong analytical skills related to working with structured and unstructured datasets
understanding of modern artificial intelligence and machine learning technologies and techniques
a demonstrated understanding of the law enforcement or national security domains


experience with modern DevSecOps tools and methodologies.

The Plant Import Operations Branch contributes towards the maintenance of the favourable health status of Australia as well as the maintenance of market access by: coordinating the implementation of national technical operational plant quarantine policy which is consistent with international and national obligations; monitoring of pathways, the technical assessment of import permit applications and issuing import permits for imported plant and plant material; developing and verifying compliance with operational policy, procedures and standards; providing consistent and science based technical advice to staff, clients and stakeholders; and the facilitation of safe importation of plants and plant material. The branch is committed to monitoring, review and improvement and adopting best practice, including using risk-return principles, innovation and project management principles.

The Biosecurity Assurance Program (BAP) identifies, develops and implements business assurance processes for the Branch to ensure import conditions are fit for purpose, biosecurity risks are managed, and business outcomes are achieved. The program is responsible for managing, reviewing and developing training and instructional material for plant import activities, identifying opportunities for risk-return on plant import pathways, through the Compliance-based Intervention Scheme (CBIS), analysing and interpreting import data to inform non-compliance action and business decision making, reviewing intelligence sources to inform changes in risk, policy and processes, managing legislation updates, performing pathway verification activities and supporting a number of other business improvement processes.

The Australian Antarctic Division (AAD) is part of the Commonwealth Department of Agriculture, Water and the Environment. As primary agency for Australia's Antarctic Program (AAP), the AAD is responsible for achieving the Australian Government's Antarctic goals. These goals are to:


The AAD also has responsibility for administering the Australian Antarctic Territory and the Territory of Heard and McDonald Islands.

The AAD Science Branch leads, conducts and supports a world class program of scientific research and environmental management, consistent with national priorities through the Australian Antarctic Science Strategic Plan. The branch provides research and advice to support Australia’s Antarctic policy objectives, including participation in the Antarctic Treaty system and other international committees, commissions and intergovernmental panels. It manages and administers the Australian Antarctic Science Program (including project requests, assessment, and reporting) and provides scientific and research advice to support regulatory and management decisions. The branch provides scientific advice for Antarctic capability projects, conducts impact assessments and develops strategies to address environmental legacies and undertakes targeted outreach promoting the value of Australian Antarctic science.

The Antarctic Climate Program investigates a range of Antarctic and Southern Ocean components of the climate system. Its team studies Antarctic atmosphere, sea ice, ice sheets and past climate using ice cores. The Antarctic Climate Program is well integrated within the Australian Antarctic Program Partnership at the University of Tasmania and holds links into the Australian Centre for Excellence in Antarctic Science, an Australian Research Council funded program.

The AAD also has responsibility for administering the Australian Antarctic Territory and the Territory of Heard and McDonald Islands.

The AAD Science Branch leads, conducts and supports a world class program of scientific research and environmental management, consistent with national priorities through the Australian Antarctic Science Strategic Plan. The branch provides research and advice to support Australia’s Antarctic policy objectives, including participation in the Antarctic Treaty system and other international committees, commissions and intergovernmental panels. It manages and administers the Australian Antarctic Science Program (including project requests, assessment, and reporting) and provides scientific and research advice to support regulatory and management decisions. The branch provides scientific advice for Antarctic capability projects, conducts impact assessments and develops strategies to address environmental legacies and undertakes targeted outreach promoting the value of Australian Antarctic science.

The Antarctic Climate Program investigates a range of Antarctic and Southern Ocean components of the climate system. Its team studies Antarctic atmosphere, sea ice, ice sheets and past climate using ice cores. The Antarctic Climate Program is well integrated within the Australian Antarctic Program Partnership at the University of Tasmania and holds links into the Australian Centre for Excellence in Antarctic Science, an Australian Research Council funded program.

The Plant Import Operations Branch contributes towards the maintenance of the favourable health status of Australia as well as the maintenance of market access by: coordinating the implementation of national technical operational plant quarantine policy which is consistent with international and national obligations; monitoring of pathways, the technical assessment of import permit applications and issuing import permits for imported plant and plant material; developing and verifying compliance with operational policy, procedures and standards; providing consistent and science based technical advice to staff, clients and stakeholders; and the facilitation of safe importation of plants and plant material. The branch is committed to monitoring, review and improvement and adopting best practice, including using risk-return principles, innovation and project management principles.

The Biosecurity Assurance Program (BAP) identifies, develops and implements business assurance processes for the Branch to ensure import conditions are fit for purpose, biosecurity risks are managed, and business outcomes are achieved. The program is responsible for managing, reviewing and developing training and instructional material for plant import activities, identifying opportunities for risk-return on plant import pathways, through the Compliance-based Intervention Scheme (CBIS), analysing and interpreting import data to inform non-compliance action and business decision making, reviewing intelligence sources to inform changes in risk, policy and processes, managing legislation updates, performing pathway verification activities and supporting a number of other business improvement processes.
